answers.body_markdown:
There are a couple of problems:

1. You&#39;re not checking that the HTTP request succeeded. **Lots** of people make this mistake, it&#39;s a flaw in the `fetch` API design, more [here](http://blog.niftysnippets.org/2018/06/common-fetch-errors.html) on my anemic little blog. You need to check `response.ok`.
2. [`response`][1] is an object with no own, enumerable properties, so `JSON.stringify` will return `&quot;{}&quot;` for it. To get the response, you must **read** the response body via one of the response object&#39;s methods, such as [`text`][2], [`json`][3], [`arrayBuffer`][4], [`formData`][5], or [`blob`][6].

So for instance:

    fetch(&quot;http://mylaravelapp.com/api/list&quot;)
    .then(response =&gt; {
        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error(&quot;HTTP error &quot; + response.status);
        }
        return response.text(); // or .json(), .arrayBuffer(), ...
    })
    .then(data =&gt; {
        console.log(JSON.stringify(data));
    })
    .catch(error =&gt; {
        console.error(error.message);
    });


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Body/text
  [3]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Body/json
  [4]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Body/arrayBuffer
  [5]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Body/formData
  [6]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Body/blob

